A: The issue is that you're calling dataSnapshot.getChildren().iterator().next() in your loop. This will always return the first child because you're creating a new iterator for each child in your loop.
Instead, you should create one iterator outside of your loop and use it to get all the children. Here's how you can do it:
Iterator<DataSnapshot> it = dataSnapshot.getChildren().iterator();
while(it.hasNext()){
    names.add(it.next().getValue(String.class));
}

This way, you're using the same iterator to get all the children and adding them to your list.

A: You are using the same iterator for all children. You should create a new iterator for each child in your loop.
Try this:
for (DataSnapshot dataSnapshot1:dataSnapshot.getChildren()) {
    Iterator<DataSnapshot> it = dataSnapshot1.getChildren().iterator();
    while(it.hasNext()){
        names.add(it.next().getValue(String.class));
    }
}

This way, you create a new iterator for each DataSnapshot in dataSnapshot.getChildren(), and use that to get all the children and add them to your list.

